{"title_page": "Josh Olson", "text_new": "\n\n{{short description|American screenwriter|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{for|the American ice hockey player|Josh Olson (ice hockey)}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name=Josh Olson\n|image=Josh Olson.jpg\n|caption = Josh Olson at the 2008 Screenwriting Expo\n|birth_date=\n|birth_place=[[United States]]\n|occupation=[[Podcast|Podcast writer]], [[Screenwriter]]\n}}\n\n'''Josh Olson''' is an American podcaster and screenwriter.\n\nJosh Olson wrote the adapted screenplay for the 2005 film ''[[A History of Violence (film)|A History of Violence]]''.{{r|low2020|olson2007}}. He was nominated for the British Academy Award<ref name=\"bafta\">{{Cite web|url=http://awards.bafta.org/award/2006/film|title=Film in 2006 &#124; BAFTA Awards|website=awards.bafta.org}}</ref>, the Writer's Guild Award<ref name=\"bafta\"/> and the Academy Award.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oscars.org/oscars/ceremonies/2006|title=The 78th Academy Awards &#124; 2006|website=Oscars.org &#124; Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences}}</ref>\n\nIn 2006, Olson collaborated with Harlan Ellison on an adaptation of the author's short story \"The Discarded\" for ABC's series, \"Masters of Science Fiction.\"<ref name=\"olson2007\">{{Cite news|last=Olson|first=Josh|url=http://www.laweekly.com/2007-10-11/news/the-life-and-death-of-jesse-james/|title=The Life and Death of Jesse James|date=10 October 2007|work=[[LA Weekly]]|access-date=29 March 2020|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181123125825/https://www.laweekly.com/news/the-life-and-death-of-jesse-james-2150689|archive-date=23 November 2018 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mastersofscifi.com/site/masters_of_science_fiction/episodes/the_discarded.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080516091648/http://www.mastersofscifi.com/site/masters_of_science_fiction/episodes/the_discarded.html|title=Masters of Science Fiction - The Discarded|date=May 16, 2008|website=MastersOfScifi.com|archivedate=May 16, 2008}}</ref> He and [[D. B. Weiss]] worked on [[Peter Jackson]]'s film based on the ''[[Halo (series)|Halo]]'' video game series, but the project was later cancelled.<ref name=\"fritz2006\">{{cite news| last=Fritz| first=Ben |date=October 31, 2006 |url=https://variety.com/2006/digital/news/no-home-for-halo-pic-1117953031/|title=No home for 'Halo' pic| work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |accessdate=October 20, 2007|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100817021747/https://www.variety.com/article/VR1117953031.html?categoryid=1043&cs=1|archive-date=17 August 2010|quote=Commercial helmer [[Neill Blomkamp]] is still aboard to direct. \"A History of Violence\" scribe Josh Olson was doing the most recent rewrite.}}</ref>\n\nOlson was hired to write an adaptation ''[[Jack Reacher (film)|Jack Reacher]]'', for [[Paramount Pictures]], part of the [[Jack Reacher]] series by [[Lee Child]].<ref>{{cite news| title=Josh Olson scripting 'One Shot'| url= https://variety.com/2008/scene/markets-festivals/josh-olson-scripting-one-shot-1117992940/ | work=Variety | first=Tatiana | last=Siegel |access-date=29 March 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329042917/https://variety.com/2008/scene/markets-festivals/josh-olson-scripting-one-shot-1117992940/|archive-date=29 March 2020|quote=Paramount Pictures has tapped \u201cA History of Violence\u201d scribe Josh Olson to adapt the Lee Child-penned mystery \u201cOne Shot.\u201d Story centers on a [[Dirty Harry]]-like homicide investigator who seeks the truth behind what seems an open-and-shut murder case after a trained [[Sniper#U.S._military|military sniper]] is arrested for shooting five random victims.}}</ref> Ultimately, the film was rewritten, and Olson received no credit on the finished movie. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/jack_reacher|title=Jack Reacher (2012)|via=www.rottentomatoes.com}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2012/film/reviews/jack-reacher-1117948893/|title=Jack Reacher|first1=Peter|last1=Debruge|first2=Peter|last2=Debruge|date=December 11, 2012}}</ref>\n\nOlson wrote two seasons of the audio drama, ''Bronzeville'', which is produced by and stars [[Laurence Fishburne]] and [[Larenz Tate]].{{r|low2020}} He is one of the hosts of the podcast, \"The Movies That Made Me\".{{r|low2020}} \n\nIn 2020, Olson started ''Rainy Day Podcasts'' with Mick Jagger, Steve Bing, and Victoria Pearman. The company has a \"first look deal\" with [[Warner Bros.|Warner Brothers]], and will produce original narrative podcasts.<ref name=\"low2020\">{{Cite news|url=https://variety.com/2020/music/news/mick-jagger-rainy-day-podcasts-warner-bros-sign-first-look-deal-1203478046/|title=Mick Jagger\u2019s Rainy Day Podcasts, Warner Bros. Digital Networks Sign First-Look Deal|last=Low|first=Elaine|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200124185502/https://variety.com/2020/music/news/mick-jagger-rainy-day-podcasts-warner-bros-sign-first-look-deal-1203478046/|url-status=live|archive-date=24 January 2020|date=2020-01-24|language=en|access-date=2020-03-29|quote=[Olson] penned two seasons of the \u201cBronzeville: audio drama, exec produced by and starring Laurence Fishburne and Larenz Tate, and co-hosts the podcast \u201cThe Movies That Made Me\u201d with director [[Joe Dante]].}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|- style=\"background:#b0c4de; text-align:center;\"\n! Year\n! Title\n! Notes\n|-\n| 2002\n| ''Infested''\n|Also Director\n|-\n| 2005\n| ''[[A History of Violence]]''\n|\n|-\n| 2007\n| ''[[Masters of Science Fiction|The Discarded]]''\n| An Episode of Masters of Science Fiction (Television)\n|-\n| 2008\n| ''[[Batman: Gotham Knight]]''\n|Anthology film segment: Have I Got a Story for You (Direct to Video)\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Cite news|url=https://www.villagevoice.com/2009/09/09/i-will-not-read-your-fucking-script/|title=I Will Not Read Your Fucking Script|work=[[The Village Voice]]|date=9 September 2009|last=Olson|first=Josh|access-date=2020-03-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180320200619/https://www.villagevoice.com/2009/09/09/i-will-not-read-your-fucking-script/|url-status=live|archive-date=20 March 2018|quote=... he wanted real criticism. They never do, of course. What they want is a few tough notes to give the illusion of honesty, and then some pats on the head. What they want \u2014 always \u2014 is encouragement, even when they shouldn\u2019t get any.}}\n\n*{{IMDb name|id=0647939|name=Josh Olson}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Olson, Josh}}\n[[Category:American male screenwriters]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "text_old": "\n\n{{short description|American screenwriter|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{for|the American ice hockey player|Josh Olson (ice hockey)}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name=Josh Olson\n|image=Josh Olson.jpg\n|caption = Josh Olson at the 2008 Screenwriting Expo\n|birth_date=\n|birth_place=[[United States]]\n|occupation=[[Podcast|Podcast writer]], [[Screenwriter]]\n}}\n\n'''Josh Olson''' is an American podcaster and screenwriter.\n\nJosh Olson wrote the adapted screenplay for the 2005 film ''[[A History of Violence (film)|A History of Violence]]''.{{r|low2020|olson2007}}. He was nominated for the British Academy Award<ref name=\"bafta\">{{Cite web|url=http://awards.bafta.org/award/2006/film|title=Film in 2006 &#124; BAFTA Awards|website=awards.bafta.org}}</ref>, the Writer's Guild Award<ref name=\"bafta\"/> and the Academy Award.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oscars.org/oscars/ceremonies/2006|title=The 78th Academy Awards &#124; 2006|website=Oscars.org &#124; Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences}}</ref>\n\nIn 2006, Olson collaborated with Harlan Ellison on an adaptation of the author's short story \"The Discarded\" for ABC's series, \"Masters of Science Fiction.\"<ref name=\"olson2007\">{{Cite news